Legume Nutrients

Corinna Hong

February 1, 2020


The U.S. Department of Agricultures FoodData Central analyzes and compiles nutrient and food component data for a wide variety of foods and beverages (U.S. Department of Agriculture, 2019). The dataset used for this project contains nutrient information for raw fruits and vegetables. This project will use the ordination method of principle component analysis to explore similarities and differences in legume and legume product nutrients.

Sacks of legumes.
Photo by Viktor Smith from Pexels. Retrieved from: https://www.pexels.com/photo/assorted-color-beans-in-sack-1393382/

# Load packages

library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)
library(naniar) # to examine NAs
library(ggfortify) # for biplot
# Read in data

nutrients <- read_csv("usda_nutrients.csv")
# Wrangle data

nutrients_wrangle <- nutrients %>% 
  clean_names() %>%
  filter(food_group == "Legumes and Legume Products") %>% 
  select(energy_kcal:zinc_mg)
# Explore missings before running PCA

naniar::gg_miss_var(nutrients_wrangle) # graph shows how many NA's for each variable (showed none for the data I have selected)
# PCA for nutrients in Legumes and Legume products

nutrients_pca <- prcomp(nutrients_wrangle, scale = TRUE)
nutrients_pca # Gives loading for every PC
summary(nutrients_pca) # Proportion of variance explained by each PC
# PC1 and PC2 together account for 47.98% of variance
nutrients_biplot <- autoplot(nutrients_pca,
                      colour = NA,
                      loadings.label = TRUE,
                      loadings.label.size = 3,
                      loadings.label.colour = "black",
                      loadings.label.repel = TRUE) + # forces labels to "repel" each other a little
  theme_minimal()

nutrients_biplot

Figure 1. PCA biplot of nutrients in legumes and legume prodcuts. Line biplot visualizing PCA results for nutrients in legumes and legume products. Lengths of each line indicate variances in the respective PC direction and angles between lines indicate correlation between nutrients. Data accessed at: https://fdc.nal.usda.gov/


Major takeaways from PCA and biplot:

  • Vitamin A, vitamin E, and Vitamin B6 have a correlation of 1 with each other.
  • Protein and zinc have a correlation of 1 with each other.
  • vitamin A, vitamin E, and Vitamin B6 have a correlation of -1 with vitamin c.
  • Iron and phosphorus are positively correlated.
  • Sugar and carbs are positivel correlated.
  • Vitamin B12 and energy have a correlation of 0.


References:
U.S. Department of Agriculture, Agricultural Research Service. FoodData Central, 2019. https://fdc.nal.usda.gov/.
